<item>
 <title>Types of Compost Bins</title>
 <link>http://understory.org/composting/types-of-bins</link>
 <description>&lt;p&gt;
&lt;img src=&quot;/files/understory/images/compost_in_bins.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;500&quot; height=&quot;375&quot; /&gt;Many different models for compost systems exist. We recommend having at least two 3&#039;x3&#039; bins, which allows for one batch of compost to finish curing while a new batch is being built.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
Features to look for include:
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;venting and air-flow into the bin (mesh or vented sides)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;cover from rain and snow&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;durability (cedar or other weather-resistant wood) &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;moving parts (the fewer moving parts, the less there is to break)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;ease of access for turning (especially if doing hot compost) and harvest&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
Questions you may ask yourself to help select a model are:
&lt;/p&gt;
